{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Word2Vec, a popular word embedding technique, emerged from RNN research to generate contextually rich word representations [48,9,50,49].",
    "Word2Vec models are designed to capture linear regularities between words in a corpus, a fundamental aspect of their architecture.",
    "These word embeddings, which capture semantic and syntactic relationships between words, are valuable features for sentiment analysis models.",
    "The performance of Word2Vec is influenced by factors such as word vector dimensionality and the size of the training data, impacting both training time and the quality of the resulting word embeddings.Training RNNs typically involves stochastic gradient descent and backpropagation through time, where the weights of the hidden layer are interpreted as representation vectors [48].",
    "Notable Word2Vec architectures include the Continuous Bag of Words (CBOW) model that removes non-linear hidden layers and employs a shared projection layer for all words, and the Continuous Skip-gram Model, which aims to maximize the prediction of a word based on its surrounding context within a sentence [48].However, training RNNs using backpropagation through time presents challenges, primarily due to the vanishing gradient problem [57]."
  ],
